---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';

const title = 'Wire Gauge / AWG Calculator';
const description = 'Free wire gauge calculator. Find ampacity, resistance per unit length, diameter and cross-sectional area for any AWG wire size.';
const intro = 'Select an AWG gauge to see its diameter, cross-sectional area, ampacity, and resistance per meter for both copper and aluminum conductors.';
const category = { id: 'engineering', name: 'Electrical Engineering' };
const faqs = [
  { q: 'What is AWG?', a: 'AWG stands for American Wire Gauge, a standardized wire sizing system used primarily in North America. Smaller AWG numbers indicate thicker wires with higher current capacity, while larger numbers indicate thinner wires.' },
  { q: 'How does AWG wire sizing work?', a: 'AWG uses a logarithmic scale where each step represents a 26% change in diameter. A decrease of 3 AWG sizes (e.g., from 10 AWG to 7 AWG) doubles the cross-sectional area. A decrease of 10 AWG sizes (e.g., 10 AWG to 1 AWG) multiplies the area by about 10.' },
  { q: 'What is ampacity?', a: 'Ampacity is the maximum current a wire can carry continuously without exceeding its temperature rating. It depends on the conductor material, insulation type, ambient temperature, and bundling with other wires.' },
  { q: 'Why does copper have higher ampacity than aluminum?', a: 'Copper has about 40% lower electrical resistance than aluminum for the same cross-sectional area. This means copper wires generate less heat for the same current, allowing them to carry higher currents safely.' },
  { q: 'What happens if I use wire with insufficient ampacity?', a: 'Using wire that is too thin for the current causes excessive heating, which can damage insulation, create fire hazards, and cause voltage drop issues. Always size wire for at least 125% of the expected continuous load.' },
  { q: 'Does wire length affect ampacity?', a: 'No, ampacity is a property of the wire itself and its installation conditions, not the length. However, longer runs increase voltage drop, which may require upsizing the wire even if ampacity is adequate.' },
  { q: 'What is the difference between stranded and solid wire?', a: 'Stranded wire consists of multiple small strands twisted together, making it more flexible and resistant to breakage from vibration. Solid wire is a single conductor, cheaper and easier to terminate, but less flexible.' },
  { q: 'How does temperature affect wire gauge selection?', a: 'Higher ambient temperatures reduce a wire\'s ampacity. The NEC provides correction factors for temperatures above 30\u00b0C (86\u00b0F). At 40\u00b0C, a wire rated for 30A may only be good for about 24A.' },
  { q: 'What is the largest AWG size?', a: 'The largest standard AWG size is 0000 (4/0), which is about 11.7 mm in diameter and can carry up to 230A for copper. Larger conductors are measured in kcmil (thousands of circular mils) rather than AWG.' },
  { q: 'Can I mix aluminum and copper wires?', a: 'Direct contact between aluminum and copper can cause galvanic corrosion. When connecting them, use approved connectors rated for both metals, and apply anti-oxidation compound. Many modern panels use copper for branch circuits.' },
];
const wireData = [
  { awg: '0000', dia: 11.684, area: 107.2, cuAmp: 230, alAmp: 180, cuOhms: 0.00016, alOhms: 0.00026 },
  { awg: '000', dia: 10.404, area: 85.0, cuAmp: 200, alAmp: 155, cuOhms: 0.00020, alOhms: 0.00033 },
  { awg: '00', dia: 9.266, area: 67.4, cuAmp: 175, alAmp: 135, cuOhms: 0.00026, alOhms: 0.00042 },
  { awg: '0', dia: 8.251, area: 53.5, cuAmp: 150, alAmp: 120, cuOhms: 0.00033, alOhms: 0.00053 },
  { awg: '1', dia: 7.348, area: 42.4, cuAmp: 130, alAmp: 100, cuOhms: 0.00041, alOhms: 0.00066 },
  { awg: '2', dia: 6.544, area: 33.6, cuAmp: 115, alAmp: 90, cuOhms: 0.00052, alOhms: 0.00084 },
  { awg: '4', dia: 5.189, area: 21.2, cuAmp: 85, alAmp: 65, cuOhms: 0.00082, alOhms: 0.00132 },
  { awg: '6', dia: 4.115, area: 13.3, cuAmp: 55, alAmp: 40, cuOhms: 0.00130, alOhms: 0.00210 },
  { awg: '8', dia: 3.264, area: 8.37, cuAmp: 40, alAmp: 30, cuOhms: 0.00208, alOhms: 0.00335 },
  { awg: '10', dia: 2.588, area: 5.26, cuAmp: 30, alAmp: 25, cuOhms: 0.00328, alOhms: 0.00529 },
  { awg: '12', dia: 2.053, area: 3.31, cuAmp: 20, alAmp: 15, cuOhms: 0.00521, alOhms: 0.00839 },
  { awg: '14', dia: 1.628, area: 2.08, cuAmp: 15, alAmp: 10, cuOhms: 0.00829, alOhms: 0.01340 },
  { awg: '16', dia: 1.291, area: 1.31, cuAmp: 10, alAmp: 5, cuOhms: 0.01320, alOhms: 0.02120 },
  { awg: '18', dia: 1.024, area: 0.823, cuAmp: 5, alAmp: 3, cuOhms: 0.02090, alOhms: 0.03380 },
  { awg: '20', dia: 0.812, area: 0.518, cuAmp: 3.5, alAmp: 2, cuOhms: 0.03320, alOhms: 0.05350 },
  { awg: '22', dia: 0.644, area: 0.326, cuAmp: 2, alAmp: 1, cuOhms: 0.05280, alOhms: 0.08510 },
  { awg: '24', dia: 0.511, area: 0.205, cuAmp: 1, alAmp: 0.5, cuOhms: 0.08390, alOhms: 0.13510 },
  { awg: '26', dia: 0.405, area: 0.129, cuAmp: 0.5, alAmp: 0.25, cuOhms: 0.13330, alOhms: 0.21480 },
  { awg: '28', dia: 0.321, area: 0.081, cuAmp: 0.3, alAmp: 0.15, cuOhms: 0.21180, alOhms: 0.34140 },
  { awg: '30', dia: 0.255, area: 0.051, cuAmp: 0.2, alAmp: 0.1, cuOhms: 0.33670, alOhms: 0.54270 },
  { awg: '32', dia: 0.202, area: 0.032, cuAmp: 0.15, alAmp: 0.05, cuOhms: 0.53520, alOhms: 0.86280 },
  { awg: '34', dia: 0.160, area: 0.020, cuAmp: 0.1, alAmp: 0.03, cuOhms: 0.85080, alOhms: 1.37140 },
  { awg: '36', dia: 0.127, area: 0.013, cuAmp: 0.05, alAmp: 0.02, cuOhms: 1.35230, alOhms: 2.18040 },
  { awg: '38', dia: 0.101, area: 0.008, cuAmp: 0.03, alAmp: 0.01, cuOhms: 2.14940, alOhms: 3.46510 },
  { awg: '40', dia: 0.080, area: 0.005, cuAmp: 0.02, alAmp: 0.005, cuOhms: 3.41670, alOhms: 5.50850 },
];
---

<ToolLayout title={title} description={description} intro={intro} category={category} faqs={faqs}>
  <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 shadow-sm sm:p-6">
    <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">AWG gauge</span>
        <select id="awg" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100">
          {wireData.map(d => <option value={d.awg}>{d.awg}</option>)}
        </select></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Conductor material</span>
        <select id="material" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100">
          <option value="cu">Copper</option><option value="al">Aluminum</option>
        </select></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Length (m)</span>
        <input id="length" type="number" step="any" placeholder="100" value="100" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100" /></label>
      <label class="block"><span class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-700">Test current (A)</span>
        <input id="current" type="number" step="any" placeholder="10" value="10" class="mt-1 w-full rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-3 outline-none focus:border-indigo-400 focus:ring-2 focus:ring-indigo-100" /></label>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-4">
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-indigo-600 p-4 text-center text-white"><div class="text-xs opacity-80">Diameter</div><div id="r-dia" class="mt-1 text-xl font-bold">\u2014</div></div>
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xs text-slate-500">Area</div><div id="r-area" class="mt-1 text-xl font-bold text-emerald-600">\u2014</div></div>
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xs text-slate-500">Resistance</div><div id="r-res" class="mt-1 text-xl font-bold text-amber-600">\u2014</div></div>
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xs text-slate-500">Ampacity</div><div id="r-amp" class="mt-1 text-xl font-bold text-slate-800">\u2014</div></div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-4 grid grid-cols-1 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xs text-slate-500">Voltage drop at test current</div><div id="r-vdrop" class="mt-1 text-lg font-bold text-slate-800">\u2014</div></div>
      <div class="rounded-xl bg-slate-50 p-4 text-center"><div class="text-xs text-slate-500">Power loss (I\u00b2R)</div><div id="r-ploss" class="mt-1 text-lg font-bold text-slate-800">\u2014</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">What different wire gauge capacity ranges mean</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Thicker wires (lower AWG numbers) carry more current. Here are typical ampacity ratings for common copper wire sizes at 60\u00b0C insulation.</p>
    <div class="mt-5 space-y-3">
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">4/0 (0000) \u2014 up to 230 A</span><span class="text-slate-400">Service entrance, main feeders</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-emerald-500" style="width:100%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">2/0 (00) \u2014 up to 175 A</span><span class="text-slate-400">Large sub-panels, heavy equipment</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-indigo-500" style="width:76%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">1 AWG \u2014 up to 130 A</span><span class="text-slate-400">Range, dryer, sub-panel feeds</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-indigo-500" style="width:57%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">6 AWG \u2014 up to 55 A</span><span class="text-slate-400">Oven, HVAC, EV charger</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-amber-500" style="width:24%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">12 AWG \u2014 up to 20 A</span><span class="text-slate-400">Lighting, outlets, general purpose</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-orange-500" style="width:9%"></div></div>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between text-sm"><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">18 AWG \u2014 up to 10 A</span><span class="text-slate-400">Low-voltage, speakers, thermostats</span></div>
        <div class="mt-1 h-3 w-full rounded-full bg-slate-100"><div class="h-3 rounded-full bg-red-500" style="width:4%"></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <figure class="mt-10">
    <svg width="800" height="200" viewBox="0 0 800 200" role="img" aria-labelledby="wg-title wg-desc" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <title id="wg-title">Wire Gauge Cross-Section Comparison</title>
      <desc id="wg-desc">Diagram comparing three wire gauge cross-sections with decreasing diameter from 10 AWG to 18 AWG</desc>
      <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="65" fill="none" stroke="#6366f1" stroke-width="3"/>
      <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="55" fill="none" stroke="#c7d2fe" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <circle cx="200" cy="100" r="32" fill="#eef2ff" stroke="#6366f1" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="200" y="100" text-anchor="middle" dominant-baseline="central" font-family="Arial,sans-serif" font-size="16" font-weight="bold" fill="#6366f1">10 AWG</text>
      <text x="200" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Arial,sans-serif" font-size="13" fill="#64748b">d = 2.59 mm</text>
      <circle cx="400" cy="100" r="45" fill="none" stroke="#475569" stroke-width="3"/>
      <circle cx="400" cy="100" r="35" fill="none" stroke="#cbd5e1" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <circle cx="400" cy="100" r="22" fill="#f8fafc" stroke="#475569" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="400" y="100" text-anchor="middle" dominant-baseline="central" font-family="Arial,sans-serif" font-size="16" font-weight="bold" fill="#475569">14 AWG</text>
      <text x="400" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Arial,sans-serif" font-size="13" fill="#64748b">d = 1.63 mm</text>
      <circle cx="600" cy="100" r="30" fill="none" stroke="#94a3b8" stroke-width="3"/>
      <circle cx="600" cy="100" r="20" fill="none" stroke="#e2e8f0" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <circle cx="600" cy="100" r="14" fill="#f1f5f9" stroke="#94a3b8" stroke-width="2"/>
      <text x="600" y="100" text-anchor="middle" dominant-baseline="central" font-family="Arial,sans-serif" font-size="14" font-weight="bold" fill="#475569">18 AWG</text>
      <text x="600" y="180" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Arial,sans-serif" font-size="13" fill="#64748b">d = 1.02 mm</text>
      <text x="400" y="30" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Arial,sans-serif" font-size="14" fill="#64748b">Wire cross-section comparison (outer = insulation, inner = conductor)</text>
    </svg>
    <figcaption class="mt-2 text-center text-sm text-slate-500">Wire gauge diameter comparison: smaller AWG = thicker wire</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <section class="mt-10 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">\u26A1</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">Electrician</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Select the right wire gauge for residential and commercial installations based on load calculations and NEC ampacity tables.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">\uD83D\uDD0A</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">Audio Installer</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Size speaker wire properly for long runs to minimize resistance and ensure full power delivery to speakers without audible loss.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">\u2600\uFE0F</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">Solar Installer</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Choose appropriate PV wire sizes for solar array strings, combiner boxes, and inverter connections to minimize I\u00b2R power loss.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
      <span class="text-2xl">\uD83D\uDEE0\uFE0F</span>
      <h3 class="mt-2 font-semibold text-slate-900">Hobbyist</h3>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Pick the right wire for DIY electronics, Arduino projects, battery banks, and automotive wiring without guesswork.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-slate-200">
    <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
      <thead class="bg-slate-50 text-slate-500"><tr><th class="p-3">AWG</th><th class="p-3">Diameter (mm)</th><th class="p-3">Area (mm\u00b2)</th><th class="p-3">Ampacity Cu (A)</th><th class="p-3">Ampacity Al (A)</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-100 text-slate-700">
        {wireData.map(d => <tr><td class="p-3 font-medium">{d.awg}</td><td class="p-3">{d.dia.toFixed(3)}</td><td class="p-3">{d.area.toFixed(2)}</td><td class="p-3">{d.cuAmp}</td><td class="p-3">{d.alAmp}</td></tr>)}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How to use the Wire Gauge Calculator</h2>
    <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">1</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Select wire size and material</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Choose the AWG gauge from the dropdown and select copper or aluminum. The chart shows all standard sizes for comparison.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">2</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Set length and test current</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Enter the conductor length and expected load current to compute voltage drop and power loss for your specific run.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-4 text-center">
        <span class="inline-flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-indigo-100 text-lg font-bold text-indigo-700">3</span>
        <h3 class="mt-3 font-semibold text-slate-900">Review the results</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Check diameter, cross-sectional area, resistance, ampacity, voltage drop, and power loss. Adjust gauge if drop exceeds your limit.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Tips for wire gauge selection</h2>
    <div class="mt-4 space-y-5">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Bigger number = thinner wire</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">AWG is counter-intuitive: 18 AWG is thinner than 12 AWG, which is thinner than 6 AWG. The scale goes backward \u2014 smaller numbers mean thicker conductors.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Always derate for bundling</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">When multiple current-carrying conductors are bundled together, heat dissipation is reduced. The NEC requires derating to 80% for 4\u20136 conductors, 70% for 7\u20139, and so on.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Consider voltage drop for long runs</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">Ampacity alone is not sufficient for long wire runs. Even if a wire can carry 30 A safely, the voltage drop over 200 ft at 120 V may exceed the recommended 3% limit.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Match insulation to environment</h3>
        <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-slate-600">THHN (90\u00b0C) is common for dry locations, while XHHW (90\u00b0C wet) is better for outdoor or damp environments. Higher temperature ratings allow higher ampacity for the same gauge.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">How AWG works</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">The American Wire Gauge (AWG) system is a standardized logarithmic scale used to designate wire diameters. Each successive gauge number corresponds to a 26% decrease in diameter. The system was originally based on the number of drawing operations needed to produce a given wire size, with higher numbers requiring more passes through smaller dies.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Key formulas</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">The diameter of an AWG wire can be calculated as: d<sub>n</sub> = 0.127 &times; 92<sup>(36-n)/39</sup> mm. The cross-sectional area doubles every 3 AWG steps (e.g., 10 AWG has half the area of 7 AWG). Resistance per unit length depends on the material resistivity and area: R = &rho; / A.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Ampacity derating</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Ampacity values shown are for single conductors in free air at 30\u00b0C ambient with 60\u00b0C insulation. In practice, derating factors apply: ambient temperature above 30\u00b0C, more than three current-carrying conductors in a cable or conduit, and insulation type with higher temperature ratings all affect the safe operating current.</p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">Why voltage drop matters at scale</h2>
    <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">In large installations, voltage drop is both a performance and economic consideration. The power lost as heat in wiring (I\u00b2R losses) can be substantial \u2014 a 200 A feeder with 2% drop loses 4 kW continuously. Upsizing wire reduces these losses and often pays for itself in energy savings over time.</p>
    <div class="mt-5 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-slate-50 p-5">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-slate-900">Worked example</h3>
      <div class="mt-2 grid gap-1 text-sm sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Wire:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">10 AWG copper</span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Diameter:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">2.588 mm</span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Cross-section:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">5.26 mm\u00b2</span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Resistance:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">0.00328 \u03a9/m (3.28 \u03a9/km)</span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Ampacity (Cu):</span> <span class="text-slate-600">30 A (60\u00b0C insulation)</span></div>
        <div><span class="font-medium text-slate-700">Typical use:</span> <span class="text-slate-600">30 A circuits, EV chargers, sub-panels</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script is:inline>
    const el = (id) => document.getElementById(id);
    const data = {
      '0000': { dia: 11.684, area: 107.2, cuAmp: 230, alAmp: 180, cuOhms: 0.00016, alOhms: 0.00026 },
      '000': { dia: 10.404, area: 85.0, cuAmp: 200, alAmp: 155, cuOhms: 0.00020, alOhms: 0.00033 },
      '00': { dia: 9.266, area: 67.4, cuAmp: 175, alAmp: 135, cuOhms: 0.00026, alOhms: 0.00042 },
